    "summary": "Vote B: Afterword, not Preface — would spoil the culminating gesture",
    "content": "**Vote: B — the Translator's Afterword.**\n\n**Reason:** This finding is a genuine philosophical contribution (the universalization and demystification of the poet-figure) and belongs in the cross-traditional connections. But it cannot go in the Preface for two reasons:\n\n1. **Spoiler concern:** The passage comes from the Appendix (Essay 8), which is the last thing the reader encounters. Discussing \"we are already poets of our own lives\" in the Preface would pre-reveal the collection's culminating gesture — the moment where the author turns from formal apparatus back to lived practice. This is structurally analogous to the Essay 3 cat punchline: the recognition that we are *already doing it* is the experiential payoff of the entire collection. Stating it in the Preface would convert a first-person recognition into a third-person proposition.\n\n2. **The Preface's scope:** The Preface orients the reader toward the essays. The poet/Dichter comparison requires the reader to have already encountered the Poetic (Essay 5), the categorical formalism (Essays 6-7), and the Appendix's closing gesture. It is interpretive commentary, not reading orientation.\n\nIn the Afterword, this belongs in the **existentialist positioning** bullet of Section B, alongside the livability point and the Being-toward-death critique. The five differences map cleanly onto the existing framework: universal (vs Ubermensch/absurd hero), creator (vs receiver of Being), self-directed (vs community-founding), medium-indifferent (vs language-bound), already-doing-it (vs called-to-authenticity). The shift from \"How do I become authentic?\" to \"How do I notice that I already am?\" is the Afterword-worthy capstone of the existentialist comparison."
  }
}
